The term is yakiniku, which means "grilled meat", and originally referred to Western barbecue. The table-grilling stuff comes from Korea, and they started referring to the concept as yakiniku after the Korean War. It's funny to me, because it's similar to a tradition in my country that's typically done at home, rather than in a specialized restaurant, and is to some the epitome of tastelessness.

Fellow writefag here.

- Little and often
- let yourself have small side projects to keep the muse entertained
- Have a goal to meet, like word count, either for a given chapter, or a given writting session.
- don't strain against a writers block, becuase sometimes you're just not in the right mind space for it.

I've also found having a story roadmap of some amount helps keep me focused, along with making sure notes are actually noted down on a separate doc so i'm not losing/wasting time searching the story for info.

Now that we're past 300, I finally got baked chicken that was sufficiently flavorful, using the BFI technique. Brute Force and Ignorance.

I mixed cayenne pepper into fat-free ranch dressing to make a dense, thick, sticky red paste. I added scorpion pepper hot sauce to it, and some garlic herb seasoning blend. I coated the chicken with the mixture, which was a bit tricky because it was so dense. Then I sprinkled them with some Tajin brand habanero lime asoning. Then I coated them with breadcrumbs and put them, as before, in a foil-lined covered pan. Cold oven, 400 F. When it gets up to temperature, one hour. Let stand and rest for 30 minutes with the lid on after removing it from the oven.

I don't know whether something odd is going on with the specific chicken I bought or whether there is something about chicken. Maybe maybe it's exuding moisture that pushes the seasoning away. It came out nicely.

I want to do Alton Brown's fried chicken recipe some time, but I don't eat a lot of fried food. It seems kind of wasteful to use so much cooking oil and then have to throw it away. Maybe I can experiment with it. My mother fried chicken in bacon grease, and did not use very much of it. She'd brown the chicken, turn it, brown it again, put a cup of water in the skillet, bring it to a boil, and then put on a tight-fitting lid. She'd simmer it 45 minutes to an hour, during which time almost all the water would boil away. Maybe I could do something like that with the buttermilk and flour coating, I dno lol. But if you have a waifur that likes chicken, and you need recipes, I'm your man.
